snippet.textDisplay:
What a stupid system. Some idiot crashes into your car and somehow it's not yours anymore and you have to pay money to get it back. THIEVES! Probably even claiming sky rocket prices to buy it back.

In Germany it stays yours and in case it's totaled you get the difference between what it was worth before the accident and what it's worth now. They provide you with few dealers that you CAN sell it to for the price that they claim it's still worth so in the end you'll never end up with a minus.

snippet.textDisplay:
I got 26k miles on my Kia Cee'd in 7 years. I haven't been driving that car for 2 years in this period because I used community transportation. It's a mess to find a parking spot in a major city nad it's faster to get into another major city by train then using the car on the autobahn during rush hour.

That facial expression of the mechanic was priceless, when I drove the car for an oil change and on the odometer was only 200+ km the previous year. He thought I was joking him. But if the service booklet says that every year you suppose to do the oil change to keep warranty you do it.

snippet.textDisplay: These old diesel German cars are so reliable. Especially so the 2.1 litre diesel from Mercedes with the 5 speed automatic. It just goes and goes without a single issue. Just change the engine and transmission oil as required (both of which are cheap to do) and it goes forever and ever. Even the interiors remain so good because the materials they used were hard wearing and high quality. We have a 2004 C220 cdi with 284,000 miles. Runs like new. Looks new inside too.
